00:05:43.359 --> 00:05:55.880
I love that. Thank you so much, Chris, for taking the time to join us today, but also thank you for all that you've done for the community as well and all the different organizations you've worked with that you've brought Posit to as well.

00:05:57.359 --> 00:06:11.480
I was thinking to get us started to learn a little bit more about your role today, it might be helpful if you could tell us a little bit about how you're developing a vision for AI initiatives at Genry and also how you're starting to get people engaged in that.

00:06:12.839 --> 00:06:22.320
Yeah, that's a good question, Rachel. So we've had a lot of focus on vision and kind of how we think about deploying and managing AI applications across our organization.

00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:30.839
And, you know, one of the ways that we think about that is to incorporate kind of two facets within that. One is obviously with a deep and concerted focus on safety.

00:06:31.760 --> 00:06:37.640
To really make sure that, for example, we're using AI in a way that doesn't lead to unintended consequences.

00:06:38.440 --> 00:06:49.320
And we also ensure that there is always human agency in the loop. So while we might look to use AI to facilitate a decision point, what we're not here to do is to use AI to make a decision.

00:06:50.279 --> 00:06:50.799
Excuse me.

00:06:51.959 --> 00:06:58.160
And so that's a little bit about the vision and how we think about AI more generally here at Genry. And

00:06:59.760 --> 00:07:05.440
can you repeat the second question, Rachel, please? Was it around how we do the meetups and startups?

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:10.160
Yeah, well, it was a little bit about how you've gotten people engaged in the vision.

00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:21.079
Yeah. So what we do is through kind of the role in global IT is we also have a deep focus on enablement and self-service data science and AI capabilities.

00:07:21.600 --> 00:07:29.320
So within our team, we do a lot of work around standing up custom AI services, in particular in the Microsoft Azure cloud.

00:07:29.839 --> 00:07:38.640
And what we do is we kind of make those services available through a variety of means, including through Posit Workbench. So we have two packages that are internal to Genry

00:07:39.200 --> 00:07:48.959
written in R and Python to enable access to a variety of those AI services. We're really looking to kind of enable business with modern AI tools and technologies

00:07:49.679 --> 00:07:55.600
to help them get started on how do we start to think about, you know, reimagining business workflows with AI at the center of that.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:07.239
And it's obviously a journey. And the way that we've started to kind of think about that is with some very tractable, you know, kind of challenges that we think and have found that generative AI seems to deliver on.

00:08:09.640 --> 00:08:22.959
Thanks, Chris. So I know in the Hangout, there's been a lot of questions around AI, but I think it's rare that we get to actually hear about the actual like use case and a few examples of how it's being used today.

00:08:23.399 --> 00:08:26.959
Would you be able to share a specific example with us?

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:35.479
Sure. Absolutely. So the one that we have is the one that we kind of started with. It's now running in production and very happy to talk about that today.

00:08:36.200 --> 00:08:42.880
So again, we started with kind of a very tractable problem that really look to use generative AI tools and technologies where they excel,

00:08:43.440 --> 00:08:48.799
which is mostly around kind of generating content, but also on its, you know, understanding of semantics and language.

00:08:49.280 --> 00:09:04.239
And the use case that we worked on and the challenge that we were looking to solve was that for our security compliance team, they receive a lot of questionnaires from external clients, mostly around our security posture. So, you know, things around encryption, etc.

00:09:04.359 --> 00:09:12.159
And what they do is they receive those incoming questions and then they'll respond to them by hand each time, or historically, that's what they have done.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:27.840
And so kind of over time, they've kind of accrued, you know, the set of question and answer pairs. And so what we did was we took that history of legally approved question and answer pairs and we put them in what's called a knowledge base. It's really just kind of a list of questions and answers matched to one another.

00:09:28.760 --> 00:09:43.479
And what we did from there was we took each of those question and answer pairs and we embedded them. So we used a large language model to essentially convert that text to a vector of floating point numbers. So we're essentially just kind of representing text with numbers.

00:09:43.479 --> 00:10:10.359
So we did that for all of the question and answer pairs. And so then when the security compliance team gets a new question that comes in the door, what we do is we embed that question as well with the same embedding model. And then we see which vector or vectors that one is most similar to. And so what we do is we see, okay, you know, we see that this new question is most similar to these 10 other, you know, question answer pairs that we've seen in the past.

00:10:10.359 --> 00:10:38.359
And what we do from there is we send that information off to a GPT model, along with some prompting, and have the GPT model reason about which one it thinks is kind of the best answer. And so this is a very tractable problem. And I think a very good one to kind of get started. It was relatively simple, you know, from kind of a technology perspective. And we were also quite confident that we could deliver on it, given our understanding of what, you know, some of these AI tools and technologies could do.

00:10:38.359 --> 00:11:06.359
And I think it's great to kind of get started in that way, in part, because you want to show kind of early success. And that's what we were able to do. Since then, we had really good customer feedback on kind of that product delivery, and has also opened up the doors for us through other teams across the Genry firm. So, you know, all of this information is publicly available. So I'm able to talk about that particular use case today. But yeah, that was kind of the first kind of foot in the door, Rachel, for us.

00:11:07.359 --> 00:11:17.359
Awesome. Thank you. Well, speaking of teams across Genry, we have a question from Nikita. Nikita, would you like to ask it?

00:11:18.359 --> 00:11:23.359
It's a little bit hard to hear you. So I'll repeat it as well. But it might be. There you go. Try again.

00:11:23.359 --> 00:11:27.359
Yeah, I have a mic. Oh, nice microphone. Okay.

00:11:27.359 --> 00:11:31.359
How do you manage international teams working on data science projects?

00:11:32.359 --> 00:11:37.359
It's a little bit hard to hear you. So I'll repeat it as well. But it might be. There you go. Try again.

00:11:37.359 --> 00:11:40.359
Yeah, I have a mic. Oh, nice microphone. Okay.

00:11:40.359 --> 00:11:45.359
How do you manage international teams working on data science projects?

00:11:46.359 --> 00:11:56.359
That's a great question, Nikita. And it's challenging, right, because we have, you know, people spanning multiple countries, multiple time zones.

00:11:56.359 --> 00:12:00.359
We have one person who is in San Diego, California.

00:12:00.359 --> 00:12:07.359
And we have other people who are located in the UK, East US, Hungary, India.

00:12:07.359 --> 00:12:18.359
We are geospatially distributed, which, you know, does kind of force us to have a very concerted effort around how do we effectively work together asynchronously.

00:12:19.359 --> 00:12:31.359
And so one of the ways that I do that is I try to kind of stack my morning meetings with folks who are in India and Europe, as an example, and try to save kind of the afternoons for folks who may be more US-based.

00:12:31.359 --> 00:12:45.359
But it is definitely a challenge to do that because, you know, we try to be respectful of, you know, everyone's time and kind of where they're physically located and try not to put too many demands on them from that perspective, because everybody needs to rest and sleep, right.

00:12:45.359 --> 00:12:57.359
And, you know, I think we've been pretty effective at that because we're very intentional with, you know, when we have meetings, when we get all the developers together at a reasonable time, that is a good fit for, you know, all parties involved.

00:12:57.359 --> 00:13:04.359
Perhaps not an ideal fit, but I think it's, you know, kind of making accommodations from time to time to facilitate that global workforce.

00:13:05.359 --> 00:13:07.359
Thank you.

00:13:07.359 --> 00:13:13.359
I see Neil has a question in the chat, and there's a little asterisk next to it, so I'll read it.

00:13:13.359 --> 00:13:20.359
But it's, if there was one AI-related skill you would recommend analysts learn, what would it be?

00:13:20.359 --> 00:13:25.359
One AI-related skill analysts learn.

00:13:26.359 --> 00:13:31.359
I guess it would be to learn more about the capabilities and limitations.

00:13:31.359 --> 00:13:46.359
Because I think what often happens is, you know, in business, people see kind of new shiny tools and technologies, and they immediately pivot to this is exactly what we need, we need AI here yesterday.

00:13:47.359 --> 00:14:00.359
And I think in some cases, you know, companies may not have data in a position where it is, you know, ideal to kind of, you know, send off to a GPT model, for example.

00:14:00.359 --> 00:14:03.359
There might be other kind of pre-processing steps that may need to happen.

00:14:04.359 --> 00:14:11.359
But I think in general, it's learning more about kind of the limitations and also where, you know, like a generative AI model excels.

00:14:11.359 --> 00:14:22.359
So it's, you know, mostly around generating content and can help you facilitate having a conversation with a body of knowledge is another way that I tend to think about generative AI models.

00:14:23.359 --> 00:14:27.359
And, you know, seeing what kind of problem spaces these models, you know, excel in.

00:14:27.359 --> 00:14:40.359
And I think it's really just around practicing with them and getting an understanding of what they can do and what they can't do to help inform, you know, okay, now that I have an understanding, what business challenge can I maybe apply this to?

00:14:40.359 --> 00:14:41.359
That's how I think about it.

00:14:43.359 --> 00:14:49.359
Thank you. I see Russ in the chat, you have a question that builds on Neil's question, if you want to go next.

00:14:50.359 --> 00:14:51.359
Yeah, thanks.

00:14:52.359 --> 00:14:54.359
I think Neil's question is really good.

00:14:54.359 --> 00:15:01.359
My interest is on the other side, what would be a really good like people skill communication skill thing that you would recommend people learn?

00:15:03.359 --> 00:15:04.359
Empathy.

00:15:06.359 --> 00:15:12.359
I think is a hallmark of kind of a well functioning team.

00:15:13.359 --> 00:15:27.359
And I think being able to kind of put yourself in the shoes of somebody else, and understand how they might be thinking how they might be feeling or why they're behaving in certain ways to not make certain attributions about surface level behaviors.

00:15:28.359 --> 00:15:47.359
For example, if somebody is running late for a meeting, where there could be dozens of explanations for that, right, we could make some internal attribution about that person, well, this person is habitually late, I can't depend on them, they're unreliable, they're not conscientious, whereas, you know, maybe something external happened that isn't something internal about that person.

00:15:48.359 --> 00:15:52.359
And so I think it's empathy, I would say.

00:15:52.359 --> 00:15:57.359
And, you know, I think that that is a critical skill for teamwork in general.

00:15:57.359 --> 00:16:02.359
And I think that is something that AI may not ever be able to replace.

00:16:03.359 --> 00:16:06.359
And I think there's something kind of uniquely human about that.

00:16:07.359 --> 00:16:15.359
And so I think in terms of, you know, the human experience and to pick kind of one kind of communication dimension to focus on for me, it'd be empathy.

00:16:17.359 --> 00:16:19.359
Sounds like Russ agrees.

00:16:19.359 --> 00:16:23.359
He said he's professional counsel in a prior career, and I agree, too.

00:16:24.359 --> 00:16:26.359
I have a question for you, Chris.

00:16:26.359 --> 00:16:27.359
Sure.

00:16:27.359 --> 00:16:37.359
How do you build a vision for your company around these AI initiatives to get buy-in from both the leadership and from the technical teams that will be tackling these?

00:16:38.359 --> 00:16:40.359
Yeah, good question.

00:16:40.359 --> 00:16:47.359
So I think that what we try to do is to kind of show early success, you know, with them.

00:16:47.359 --> 00:16:57.359
And that helps get kind of buy-in around, okay, maybe we're going to start with kind of standing up some initial tools and technologies that are just out there for people to use, right?

00:16:57.359 --> 00:17:06.359
So, for example, we have here Azure OpenAI, which we make available through AI Studio, Azure AI Studio.

00:17:06.359 --> 00:17:15.359
And what people are able to do with that is to go in and to experiment and to see kind of what the capabilities are and, again, learn about, you know, how do I think about prompting?

00:17:15.359 --> 00:17:17.359
How do I think about system prompts?

00:17:17.359 --> 00:17:25.359
You know, how do I think about customizing, you know, some of the parameters that can kind of control the outputs from some of these models?

00:17:26.359 --> 00:17:32.359
So I think it's largely about showing initial success and then kind of taking that on the road.

00:17:33.359 --> 00:17:42.359
But I think critically important to that is having executive sponsorship for it because it has to come, in my mind, in large part from senior leadership.

00:17:42.359 --> 00:17:49.359
So someone who kind of recognizes the value of, you know, kind of what generative AI models can do.

00:17:49.359 --> 00:17:58.359
And then also discussing more broadly across the organization on, you know, some of the use cases that they perceive they have where AI could be relevant.

00:17:58.359 --> 00:18:01.359
And in some cases they are, but in some cases they're not.

00:18:01.359 --> 00:18:16.359
And what we would try to do is to kind of peel off the ones that we think, you know, would have, you know, kind of an impact on revenue or a large impact on efficiency and think about prioritization of those AI projects in that way.

00:18:19.359 --> 00:18:20.359
Thank you.

00:18:20.359 --> 00:18:22.359
Ailee, I see you have a question in the chat.

00:18:22.359 --> 00:18:23.359
Do you want to jump in here?

00:18:23.359 --> 00:18:24.359
Sure.

00:18:25.359 --> 00:18:26.359
Yeah.

00:18:26.359 --> 00:18:35.359
So, Chris, I'm sort of after picking your brain a little bit because I've recognized that AI is being increasingly used.

00:18:36.359 --> 00:18:47.359
But I struggle to understand exactly what AI is and also to think about how it might be implemented in sort of my field and others field.

00:18:47.359 --> 00:18:50.359
And so I was so I work in infectious disease modeling.

00:18:51.359 --> 00:18:54.359
And so we're all familiar with everything that happened during COVID.

00:18:55.359 --> 00:19:11.359
And I just kind of think about the future and the next pandemic and sort of want to brainstorm a little bit about how we could use AI to make the responses better or just improve our modeling, improve our responses.

00:19:12.359 --> 00:19:18.359
But it's a bit overwhelming to figure out how to start because there's all these different models out there.

00:19:19.359 --> 00:19:20.359
There's chat GPT.

00:19:20.359 --> 00:19:22.359
There's other versions that are better for certain things.

00:19:22.359 --> 00:19:29.359
And so I guess my question to you is just where's a good place to start and what are important pitfalls to avoid?

00:19:29.359 --> 00:19:31.359
Yeah, good question, Kylie.

00:19:31.359 --> 00:19:36.359
I think that definitions of AI vary widely.

00:19:36.359 --> 00:19:41.359
Some people would even go so far as to say that linear regression is a form of AI.

00:19:42.359 --> 00:19:45.359
I don't know how I feel about that quite yet.

00:19:45.359 --> 00:19:58.359
But I wonder, Kylie, if we're kind of in the train of kind of more traditional statistical approaches because a lot of the kind of GPT models, again, kind of what they specialize in is in generating content.

00:19:59.359 --> 00:20:05.359
So you think about things like drafting an email or drafting a paper.

00:20:05.359 --> 00:20:13.359
That's not to say that they can't help in other ways, too, because we're also using it to kind of pluck out certain pieces of information from a body of text.

00:20:13.359 --> 00:20:16.359
So there are kind of various domains where they can be applied.

00:20:17.359 --> 00:20:36.359
I think that, you know, at least in my experience, I've seen those models applied less to kind of the kind of challenges that you're talking about with kind of COVID response, but to the extent that it could apply to kind of generating content, you know, for people to kind of understand, okay, you know, how do I draft this message for particular audiences?

00:20:37.359 --> 00:20:48.359
Or kind of given these, you know, variables or characteristics that I want to highlight in a message, you know, I can include that as part of my, you know, drafting of content through a GPT model, let's say.

00:20:49.359 --> 00:20:53.359
So I think there's, you know, different use cases depending on the type of AI that we're talking about here.

00:20:54.359 --> 00:21:01.359
The ones that we tend to focus, you know, most here at Genry is on kind of the large language models and generative AI.

00:21:02.359 --> 00:21:04.359
Okay. And then just a quick follow up.

00:21:04.359 --> 00:21:26.359
So if they're really good at generating content, do you think they could then be applied to sort of analyzing large bodies of text, such as tweets, scoots, whatever, to see what, to kind of get an idea of what people's sort of perception is.

00:21:27.359 --> 00:21:37.359
So could it sort of flip around and rather than generating the content to share, could it take the content and then say, okay, this is how people are feeling about X, Y, or Z?

00:21:38.359 --> 00:21:41.359
Yeah, I think that would be a reasonable use case for tools like this.

00:21:42.359 --> 00:21:48.359
And so not only can it kind of expand, right, in terms of generating content, but it can also summarize content as well.

00:21:49.359 --> 00:21:51.359
And it's very, very good at that as well, arbitrary content.

00:21:51.359 --> 00:22:00.359
And I think where, you know, I would maybe get started with that is kind of, you know, seeing what set of instructions I can kind of pass along to the GPT model as well through prompt engineering.

00:22:01.359 --> 00:22:10.359
You know, people sometimes refer to that as, but it's really just kind of a set of instructions that you pair with the content that you're sending to those models to kind of achieve the result that you're looking to achieve.

00:22:11.359 --> 00:22:14.359
Which in this case, it may be, you know, some type of sentiment analysis.

00:22:15.359 --> 00:22:24.359
It sounds like you're hinting at here perhaps, but, you know, it can be, you know, summarizing that content to kind of give, you know, its assessment of whatever dimension that you might be curious about.

00:22:25.359 --> 00:22:26.359
Great. Thanks.

00:22:27.359 --> 00:22:28.359
Sure. Good questions.

