00:23:01.359 --> 00:23:02.359
And these are running all over the world.

00:23:02.359 --> 00:23:08.359
And by and large, that's where the bulk of our work gets done around kind of these single virtual machine servers.

00:23:09.359 --> 00:23:13.359
However, sometimes people do need to work with data that are stored in other locations.

00:23:14.359 --> 00:23:19.359
For example, we have a lot of data stored in our data lakes, again, that are geospatially distributed.

00:23:20.359 --> 00:23:25.359
And we support working with those data in the data lake through two different options.

00:23:26.359 --> 00:23:33.359
The first is that people can directly read from the data lake and write to the data lake directly from Posit Workbench, as an example.

00:23:34.359 --> 00:23:43.359
But they can also pull data, irrespective of whether they're aggregated, from the data lake, which of course gives them the option to push compute to big data tools and technologies.

00:23:44.359 --> 00:23:50.359
I don't want to get into necessarily the semantics of what big data is, so I just kind of refer to them loosely as, you know, big data tools and technologies.

00:23:51.359 --> 00:23:58.359
One of the more recent developments, of course, that I'm particularly excited about is Posit's integration with Databricks' Unity Catalog.

00:23:59.359 --> 00:24:10.359
If you haven't heard of Unity Catalog, some of you on the call may not have, it's effectively a data governance layer for granular control and managing data assets that exist within a Databricks environment.

00:24:11.359 --> 00:24:23.359
And a few of our teams have now proved that capability, where we've actually used Posit Workbench to connect to Unity Catalog and be able to query and work with data and views that sit on top of our data lake.

00:24:24.359 --> 00:24:28.359
And Rachel, we're doing a lot more on operational reporting today on this.

00:24:29.359 --> 00:24:34.359
And so if the data are, you know, kind of smallish, then what we do is we, you know, have Workbench connect to Unity Catalog directly.

00:24:35.359 --> 00:24:39.359
We just kind of specify a catalog, a schema, and a table.

00:24:40.359 --> 00:24:50.359
And then we can, you know, from that perspective, have the opportunity to kind of write dplyr code against that, and that dplyr code can be converted to Spark SQL or other flavors of SQL.

00:24:51.359 --> 00:24:54.359
And we can pull those data back to Posit, so we can do compute locally on the server.

00:24:55.359 --> 00:25:00.359
And then we can, you know, in some cases, what we're doing today is we're then writing that output to PINs.

00:25:01.359 --> 00:25:08.359
I know there might be some PINs aficionados on the call today, which ultimately, in turn, serves some of our Power BI reporting that we do.

00:25:09.359 --> 00:25:18.359
If the data are larger, however, sometimes what we'll do is, you know, kind of lean almost entirely on kind of that Databricks specific workflow.

00:25:18.359 --> 00:25:24.359
So we'll have kind of the Posit Workbench kickoff, you know, jobs that run on the Databricks clusters.

00:25:25.359 --> 00:25:30.359
So a lot of what we're doing kind of on the Posit and Databricks front is around self-service reporting.

00:25:31.359 --> 00:25:38.359
And I really look forward to, you know, kind of the possibilities that stem through that, perhaps offloading arbitrary R workloads to Databricks.

00:25:39.359 --> 00:25:53.359
So, you know, the way that we're starting to think about this is how do we kind of enable, you know, business using, you know, premier data science tools and technologies with data that we always, as kind of a matter of habit, store in our data lake or central data repositories.

00:25:54.359 --> 00:25:55.359
Thanks, Chris.

00:25:56.359 --> 00:26:10.359
Something that has come up for me in talking with teams is, regardless of what the tools are, but I guess in this case, Databricks and Posit, sometimes they're managed by different teams and it's hard to bring both sides together.

00:26:11.359 --> 00:26:16.359
And I was wondering if you have any kind of recommendations for some of us who may be trying to do that.

00:26:17.359 --> 00:26:20.359
So when you say bring the teams together, Rachel, do you mean business teams and IT teams?

00:26:21.359 --> 00:26:29.359
So I guess in this specific example, if there's one team who's managing the Databricks implementation, but a different team is managing Posit.

00:26:30.359 --> 00:26:45.359
Yeah, I think we're in maybe a fortuitous position because the team who manages our data lake and the team who manages the data science tools and technologies, the Posit stack in particular, we all exist within the same IT tower.

00:26:46.359 --> 00:26:48.359
So we all roll up to the same manager, which is great.

00:26:48.359 --> 00:26:50.359
So we have routine touch points.

00:26:51.359 --> 00:26:57.359
We meet once a week to discuss anything that may exist at the intersection of management activities, but in particular.

00:26:58.359 --> 00:27:02.359
And in fact, just this last week, we had a discussion on Posit Workbench and the data lake.

00:27:03.359 --> 00:27:08.359
And so kind of from then we met offline, we clarified some approaches, and it was very easy to get alignment.

00:27:09.359 --> 00:27:13.359
I think it may not be that way at every company, though, which could be a challenge.

00:27:13.359 --> 00:27:20.359
But I think at least in terms of how IT is structured here at Genry, it is amenable to kind of facilitating that communication.

00:27:21.359 --> 00:27:24.359
Thank you. Libby, I'll pass it over to you for the next one.

00:27:25.359 --> 00:27:28.359
Yeah, I see Michelle had a great question and it has asterisks.

00:27:29.359 --> 00:27:30.359
So I'm going to go ahead and read it.

00:27:31.359 --> 00:27:37.359
And it's, have you had tools that were deployed into production and ended up providing inaccurate or bad results?

00:27:38.359 --> 00:27:42.359
And if so, how did you regain trust in the tool with your stakeholders?

00:27:44.359 --> 00:27:45.359
Inaccurate or bad results?

00:27:46.359 --> 00:27:48.359
I mean, I think that, sure, absolutely.

00:27:49.359 --> 00:27:53.359
I mean, we, you know, and thinking back to kind of my days at Carfax, right?

00:27:54.359 --> 00:27:58.359
So we would, you know, try to predict the price of a used vehicle given its vehicle attributes.

00:27:59.359 --> 00:28:05.359
And we never were able to perfectly predict, you know, what that, you know, car would go for ultimately.

00:28:06.359 --> 00:28:07.359
And so it's really just kind of projection.

00:28:08.359 --> 00:28:12.359
So there's an inherent amount of error, you know, kind of within that process, although we give kind of our best guesses.

00:28:13.359 --> 00:28:21.359
So I think the way to kind of do that is put some metrics around, you know, how much error there is and why that's expected.

00:28:22.359 --> 00:28:23.359
And to try to manage that effectively.

00:28:24.359 --> 00:28:31.359
So to try to help, you know, have people manage expectations around, okay, you know, here's why we're maybe seeing, you know, some of these errors and some of our predictions.

00:28:32.359 --> 00:28:45.359
Here at GenRe, you know, I think that in some cases, we do see errors as well, because we're, you know, not always going to, you know, suggest the right answer to a net new incoming question for our security compliance team.

00:28:46.359 --> 00:28:51.359
But they're also able to see that, although it's not 100% accurate, we are doing pretty well.

00:28:52.359 --> 00:29:00.359
We're doing, you know, 90% accuracy, which in the grand scheme of things, if you can populate, you know, 90% of responses accurately, that's going to save them a lot of time.

00:29:01.359 --> 00:29:04.359
From having to kind of go through and identifying those answers on their own.

00:29:05.359 --> 00:29:09.359
And of course, you know, they also have to vet kind of the veracity of those responses.

00:29:10.359 --> 00:29:11.359
So there's human agency within that loop.

00:29:12.359 --> 00:29:22.359
So again, although we're kind of automatically, you know, suggesting options and facilitating a decision point, a human still has the ultimate oversight on kind of what goes out the door, so to speak, in an email.

00:29:23.359 --> 00:29:28.359
So I think it's, you know, although we're going to see errors all the time, or we're going to see outright fabrications.

00:29:28.359 --> 00:29:39.359
But I think it's, you know, mostly around end user education and helping people manage expectations and showing them kind of how the positives kind of outweigh the negatives in terms of output.

00:29:41.359 --> 00:29:42.359
Thanks, Chris.

00:29:43.359 --> 00:29:48.359
I saw there was a question on Slido, and I realized I accidentally went to last week's Slido.

00:29:49.359 --> 00:29:56.359
But for this week, the question was, how do you protect your own and your team's well-being at work?

00:29:57.359 --> 00:29:59.359
That is a great question.

00:30:00.359 --> 00:30:05.359
So let me think how I want to kind of respond to that.

00:30:06.359 --> 00:30:15.359
So I'm a social psychologist, and I've long been interested in why people do what they do when they're around other people.

00:30:16.359 --> 00:30:17.359
That's what I studied.

00:30:18.359 --> 00:30:23.359
And I try to take an evidence-based approach to that to inform what I think and what I do.

00:30:24.359 --> 00:30:36.359
And even as recently as this week, you know, we had an all-hands kind of team meeting where I've kind of called out a lot of topics related to what's referred to as psychological safety.

00:30:37.359 --> 00:30:42.359
And a lot of my kind of previous management ethos was guided by self-determination theory.

00:30:43.359 --> 00:30:52.359
So this was, you know, some early kind of motivational theories kind of back in the 90s, where they had kind of a deep focus on, you know, facilitating basic human needs that we all share.

00:30:53.359 --> 00:31:02.359
You know, a need for autonomy or having a sense of control, a need for competency, you know, a need to feel like you are able to execute on something effectively, and a need for relatedness.

00:31:03.359 --> 00:31:07.359
You know, the ability to connect, you know, with one another in meaningful ways.

00:31:08.359 --> 00:31:11.359
And we had a lot of deliberate kind of implementations around that, right?

00:31:12.359 --> 00:31:19.359
So I try to give people high-level challenges and be a collaborator rather than dictate to them what they should do or how to solve a solution.

00:31:20.359 --> 00:31:23.359
Because ultimately, you know, they're super smart and very good at what they do as well.

00:31:24.359 --> 00:31:26.359
You know, I give positive feedback on their skills and abilities.

00:31:27.359 --> 00:31:33.359
And we also have, you know, dedicated coffee chats where once a month, we all get together for a half hour.

00:31:34.359 --> 00:31:36.359
And my only rule is we don't talk about work.

00:31:37.359 --> 00:31:38.359
We could talk about anything else but work.

00:31:39.359 --> 00:31:44.359
And so, you know, it's really with an eye toward kind of helping people, you know, feel comfortable with one another.

00:31:45.359 --> 00:31:50.359
And, you know, again, more recently, I've had a deeper focus on these ideas of psychological safety in the team.

00:31:50.359 --> 00:32:01.359
And the general kind of thrust behind this is that there's a shared belief held by members of a team that the team is safe for interpersonal risk-taking.

00:32:02.359 --> 00:32:18.359
So in that context, when I'm talking about interpersonal risks, what I'm referring to here is the ability to speak up, to offer ideas, to admit mistakes, ask for help, provide candid feedback, share worries and concerns.

00:32:19.359 --> 00:32:24.359
Without there being any fear of consequence for that.

00:32:25.359 --> 00:32:29.359
And this is something that is supported by decades of research, actually.

00:32:30.359 --> 00:32:37.359
So if you go back to like even the mid-60s, there was some, you know, early pioneering work at kind of psychological safety at an individual level.

00:32:38.359 --> 00:32:45.359
But more recently in kind of the late 90s, Amy Edmondson had kind of a series of papers on psychological safety at a team level.

00:32:45.359 --> 00:32:49.359
And as it turns out, it's predictive of a lot of things that you probably would care about, right?

00:32:50.359 --> 00:32:52.359
It's basically correlated with getting stuff done.

00:32:53.359 --> 00:33:03.359
So it's very highly correlated with engagement and task performance, information sharing, creativity, the desire for people to learn, how happy they are, you know, showing up to work.

00:33:04.359 --> 00:33:15.359
And, you know, being in kind of the position that I'm in, I take it as a very serious responsibility to kind of protect my team in kind of that way and to make sure they have that space where they can be themselves.

00:33:16.359 --> 00:33:21.359
Where we can celebrate individual differences and, you know, show up to work and know it's okay to not be okay.

00:33:22.359 --> 00:33:24.359
Like these are things that I care very deeply about.

00:33:25.359 --> 00:33:28.359
And, you know, it permeates, you know, a lot of the messaging that I have within the team.

00:33:28.359 --> 00:33:30.359
So I think that's a great question.

00:33:31.359 --> 00:33:33.359
And that's some of the ways that I try to approach it.

00:33:34.359 --> 00:33:37.359
And we were excited for this journey.

00:33:38.359 --> 00:33:39.359
I just presented on some of these ideas to the team.

00:33:40.359 --> 00:33:45.359
And so we're going to now start to kind of think through for our team specifically, you know, how do we implement it?

00:33:46.359 --> 00:33:48.359
I think we've already started to do that, but how do we implement it?

00:33:49.359 --> 00:33:50.359
And then more importantly, how do we sustain it?

00:33:51.359 --> 00:33:52.359
Fantastic.

00:33:53.359 --> 00:34:00.359
I was going to my next question was going to be like, how does your background in psychology kind of affect the way that you lead?

00:34:01.359 --> 00:34:04.359
But I think that you fully answered that question with your answer.

00:34:05.359 --> 00:34:12.360
So I would love to actually throw to another one of my favorite social science people, Alan, to ask your question.

00:34:15.360 --> 00:34:16.360
Thanks, Libby.

00:34:17.360 --> 00:34:18.360
Hi, Chris.

00:34:19.360 --> 00:34:24.360
You're related to the sort of team development and team interaction angle from the sort of people's roles perspective.

00:34:25.360 --> 00:34:34.360
I'm curious if as you've gotten into more of the large language model, the Gen AI stuff, has that resulted in distinct changes in people's roles?

00:34:35.360 --> 00:34:41.360
How is the balance of sort of pre-LLM work changed, if at all?

00:34:42.360 --> 00:34:46.360
Are you doing a lot of that same stuff or has that drawn down as LLM related stuff has come up?

00:34:46.360 --> 00:34:53.360
And sort of overall, what kind of impact does that have on the way you design the team or describe your roles or let people specialize, that sort of thing?

00:34:54.360 --> 00:34:58.360
Yeah, I would say, Alan, you know, kind of more similar than dissimilar.

00:34:59.360 --> 00:35:11.360
You know, I think that, you know, the idea of a, you know, kind of solution architect, full stack engineer, data engineer, like these, these roles have been around for a while, as has like MLOps, you know, for example, as a practice.

00:35:12.360 --> 00:35:22.360
And it's kind of a natural extension in some ways of some of those roles, but applied to, you know, kind of this domain specific area of, you know, generative AI.

00:35:23.360 --> 00:35:32.360
And, you know, there's still a deep focus, you know, at least on our team on, you know, how do we get all of these modular independent pieces to communicate with one another?

00:35:33.360 --> 00:35:34.360
You know, how are we going to stitch together this solution?

00:35:34.360 --> 00:35:41.360
You know, how are we going to think intelligently about, you know, how do I, you know, implement, you know, the right chunking strategy or splitting up my document?

00:35:42.360 --> 00:35:47.360
How do I put in the right tags? How do I add the right metadata to make searching, you know, more efficient?

00:35:48.360 --> 00:35:52.360
So these are, these are things that we, you know, think about, you know, quite a bit, and we do a lot of experimentation around it.

00:35:53.360 --> 00:36:11.360
And I think it's kind of a natural extension in some ways of what, you know, a more traditional data scientist, you know, might do, but just apply to this other domain, which is ripe with uncertainty and ambiguity, which makes it both fun and nerve wracking, you know, at times, Alan, because we don't know exactly what's going to happen.

00:36:12.360 --> 00:36:23.360
And, but it's pretty cool to kind of operate in that space, to be able to lead, you know, kind of a modernization within the company, generally, and that's quite an exciting opportunity that we have.

00:36:25.360 --> 00:36:26.360
That's great. Thank you. I appreciate hearing that.

00:36:27.360 --> 00:36:28.360
Sure.

00:36:29.360 --> 00:36:43.360
I want to go back to the idea or the topic of psychological safety, because I see, Darren, you shared a link in the chat that's getting a lot of love. And I just want to make sure that's part of the recording as well. Darren, do you want to talk about that briefly?

00:36:44.360 --> 00:36:49.360
Yeah, so I'm glad to see that there's a lot of appreciation for this topic. And Chris, thanks for bringing it up.

00:36:50.360 --> 00:37:05.360
So, this was on my mind a few months ago, and I brought it up with my team as it relates to pull requests, because, you know, everyone feels a little bit differently about how their code is critiqued and the feedback they receive.

00:37:06.360 --> 00:37:15.360
And it's not just how it's been received, but it's also how it's been given. So understanding how people receive feedback and how people appreciate it in different ways is really important to understand.

00:37:15.360 --> 00:37:42.360
And I'll have Rachel or Olivia reshare that link if it gets buried in the chat, but there's like a triangle of psychological safety when it comes to anxiety with code review and how you respond to it and how the result of how you behave as a result of feedback presents itself in different ways for different people, depending on how they respond.

00:37:45.360 --> 00:38:03.360
And so creating resources for people or providing resources for people to understand how to work through that and work through it in a positive way, I think it's really, really important for building a really functional team.

00:38:04.360 --> 00:38:20.360
Yeah, I agree, Darren. And I think that's a great point. You know, I think there's an inherent tradeoff between what is best for the individual and what is best for the team, in some cases, not always, but in some cases, right?

00:38:20.360 --> 00:38:33.360
So, like, if I'm out there constantly admitting mistakes, I'm out there, you know, constantly saying, hey, I screwed that up, and actually did this in front of my team, you know, when I talked about this the other day, I went through like three mistakes I've made very recently, right?

00:38:33.360 --> 00:38:46.360
And it talked about the consequences of those. And so that's hard to do, Darren, right? Like, it's hard for people to admit mistakes, because the interpersonal risk there, right, is that people start to view you as incompetent, or they view you as less capable in some ways.

00:38:46.360 --> 00:38:59.360
But at the same time, I think it establishes trust, too, because we all know that we make mistakes. You know, maybe we don't celebrate them as publicly all the time, but we're all fundamentally human, and we all fundamentally make mistakes.

00:39:00.360 --> 00:39:24.360
And I don't think that anyone truly shows up with the intent to sabotage, you know, a work team, necessarily. But it's kind of this idea, Darren, where, you know, if we can get kind of increasingly comfortable with being uncomfortable, you know, kind of in those moments, you know, I think it's, again, I'm not saying it's easy to do or easy to sustain, I think it's a real challenge, which is why I'm excited to take this on with our team.

00:39:24.360 --> 00:39:49.360
But I think that, you know, coming from a leadership perspective, you know, someone can help kind of set that context and can reinforce, you know, certain behaviors of what they want to see, and have broader team discussions around it. Like, hey, how are we going to deal with, you know, how are we going to think about, you know, how someone might react to feedback on a pull request? You know, how can we be more empathetic to, like, how might someone receive this message, given whatever context or history there might be in the team?

00:39:49.360 --> 00:39:58.360
So I think those are all important considerations. And, you know, certainly something to be thoughtful about, because there's, you know, definitely a lot of contextual factors at play there.

00:39:59.360 --> 00:40:15.360
Yeah, I would just add to, you know, the environment that you're in with your team, Chris, like, you want to make sure that it's, before you even have this discussion of anxiety related to pull requests, that the team feels comfortable talking about those things. And to do that, you have to talk about things outside of work.

00:40:15.360 --> 00:40:41.360
And so we do something similar, where we have a weekly catch up meeting with my team. And the first 15 minutes is just like an open question, like, here's a question of the week. And the last week that we did, it was like, what TV show are you watching recently? Or like, what's your favorite holiday? Or, you know, that kind of thing, just to kind of set the tone of having some personal relationships that are built as a foundation before you can have discussions related to anxiety, which is a very personal thing.

00:40:41.360 --> 00:41:01.360
It is, it is. And, you know, let's face it, we spend a tremendous amount of time with our teammates, more time than we probably spend with anybody else. And so, you know, to the extent that I can help control, you know, how people feel coming into work, and them finding work meaningful, you know, showing up with this expectation that I can be me.

00:41:01.360 --> 00:41:29.360
Right, and I don't need to be, you know, I can show up with my concerns, my worries, my insecurities, my anxieties, I can show up with all of that. And I know that I'll still be accepted on the team. So that's what I'm, you know, working toward. And it's a hard challenge, Darren, I would say, you know, and because, you know, again, I think there's an inherent conflict there between, you know, maybe what's best for us individually, and you know, what ultimately leads to kind of better team outcomes.

00:41:30.360 --> 00:41:38.360
Thank you. Moro, I see you have a follow up along question here. And I'd love to have you jump in here.

00:41:38.360 --> 00:41:55.360
Thank you. Thanks, Rachel. Yeah, I'm excited about this topic. I think I'm a struggler in a way. And I've seen other strugglers. So again, I can tell when I see a struggler in this in this area, it looks like a great idea. I would like love to read more.

00:41:56.360 --> 00:42:18.360
But I've seen people including myself wanting to promote that psychological safety, particularly across cultures, it's very hard to even predict how the person is going to take what you say. So I wonder, you know, what advice could you be, could you give that is kind of general enough that, you know, international team, someone who wants to promote can get there?

00:42:19.360 --> 00:42:36.360
Yeah, no, that's a good call. And again, I think it's, you know, really important to be knowledgeable and insightful about respecting individual differences, you know, because we're all from different backgrounds. But that's what's unique about us. And it makes, you know, everyone like so special and can bring these unique contributions to the team.

00:42:36.360 --> 00:43:05.360
I know that Hofstede's had kind of a lot of work around, you know, kind of individual differences in culture. Since then, you know, I haven't really kept up maybe as much as I should, with some of the kind of cross cultural, you know, psychological implications there. But, you know, more around, I think just being kind of knowledgeable about individual differences in the team, kind of what their values, you know, are, you know, how they think about things like what, what, you know, maybe promotes their anxieties or makes them feel uncomfortable.

00:43:06.360 --> 00:43:31.360
And, you know, definitely, you know, and because we have that on our team as well. And, you know, we, you know, people who are from India originally, and again, someone's in Hungary, in Budapest, and, you know, we're all over the world. And we all come from different cultures and backgrounds and, you know, schools of thought, and, you know, certainly something to be mindful about, I would say, you know, how do we kind of take that into account when thinking through this at a team level?

00:43:31.360 --> 00:43:56.360
You know, it's not a, not a one size fits all, Mauro, I don't, you know, intend to, you know, kind of paint that picture here. But it but it's also interesting, because there, there was this study at Google, you know, because, you know, Amy Edmondson's her early work back in the late 90s, this was on kind of a, like an office, you know, manufacturing store where she did this initial study and saw kind of the merits of psychological safety.

00:43:56.360 --> 00:44:16.360
But, you know, Google also has poured millions of dollars into understanding kind of what makes teams effective. And in 2012, they had a study called Project Aristotle, where they looked at, you know, over 150 teams, they, you know, they looked at, you know, a multitude of factors to see what could, you know, create the perfect team.

00:44:16.360 --> 00:44:45.360
And they, you know, the conventional wisdom was all around individual differences, right? So, you know, does it matter that, you know, I pair people who are extroverted, or people who have the same academic pedigree, or people who, you know, enjoy hanging out on the weekends? It doesn't matter how long they've been at the company, you know, so all these individual differences, and kind of what they found through that is that, you know, who they are does not matter. And in terms of those individual differences, it's in what they found was that the single best predictor of team performance, believe it or not, more than a third of the time, they're not going to be able to predict a team performance.

00:44:45.360 --> 00:45:13.360
Believe it or not, Mauro was psychological safety, that was the most important factor for team outcomes. And, you know, it just blows me away. You know, because it's, it's kind of an interesting idea, though, because in some small way, like it reminds me of, you know, just being kind of validated for who you are. And, you know, having that kind of, you know, lead to better team outcomes, you know, and it's kind of the freedom to be you. And that's, it's not that way everywhere, right?

00:45:13.360 --> 00:45:42.360
